ist of Canadian short story writers]]\n* [[List of Canadian science fiction authors]]\n* [[List of Canadian historians]]\n* [[List of Canadian women writers in French]]\n* [[List of Quebec writers]]\n* [[List of French Canadian writers from outside Quebec]]\n* [[List of famous Canadians]]\n* [[Lists of authors]]\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{citation | last = Heath | first =Jeffrey M | year = 1991| title =Profiles in Canadian Literature, Volume 7\n  | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=qmMRJzrllTwC&lpg=PP1&dq=Canadian%20literature&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true | publisher=Dundurn Press | isbn=1-55002-145-1 | accessdate = }}\n* {{citation | last =  Stouck| first =David | year =1988 | title =Major Canadian authors : a critical introduction to Canadian literature in English | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=R3tTsYA5DZ0C&lpg=PP1&dq=Canadian&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=true | publisher= University of Nebraska Press | isbn=0-8032-4119-4| edition=2nd | accessdate = }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110103231604/http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/writers/index-e.html Introduction - Canadian Writers] - Library and Archives Canada\n* [http://canadian-writers.athabascau.ca Canadian Writers - Athabasca University]\n\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Lists of writers by nationality}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Canadian writers| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of Canadian people by occupation|Writers]]\n[[Category:Lists of writers by nationality|Canada]]\n", "name_user": "LiteratureCompanion", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eT:+ Toye", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Canadian_writers"}
{"title_page": "2016 Georgia Bulldogs football team", "text_new": "{{short description|American college football season}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NCAA team season\n| mode = football\n| year = 2016\n| team = Georgia Bulldogs\n| image = Georgia Athletics logo.svg\n| image_size = 150\n| conference = Southeastern Conference\n| division = Eastern Division\n| short_conf = SEC\n| CoachRank = \n| APRank = \n| CFPRank =\n| record = 8\u20135\n| conf_record = 4\u20134\n| head_coach = [[Kirby Smart]]\n| hc_year = 1st\n| off_coach =[[Jim Chaney]]\n| oc_year =1st\n| def_coach =[[Mel Tucker]]\n| dc_year = 1st\n| off_scheme = [[Pro-style offense|Pro-style]]\n| def_scheme = [[3\u20134 defense|3\u20134]]\n| captain=Nick Chubb<br>Brandon Kublanow<br>[[Sony Michel]]<br>Maurice Smith\n| stadium = [[Sanford Stadium]]<br>(Capacity: 92,746)\n| champion = Liberty Bowl champion\n| conf_champ = \n| conf_champ_result = \n| bowl = [[2016 Liberty Bowl (December)|Liberty Bowl]] \n| bowl_result = W 31\u201323 vs. [[2016 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU]]\n}}\n{{2016 SEC football standings}}\nThe '''2016 Georgia Bulldogs football team''' represented the [[University of Georgia]] in the [[2016 NCAA Division I FBS football season]]. The Bulldogs played their home games at [[Sanford Stadium]]. They were members of the Eastern Division of the [[Southeastern Conference]]. They were led by first-year head coach [[Kirby Smart]]. They finished the season 8\u20135, 4\u20134 in SEC play to finish in a three-way tie for second place in the Eastern Division. They were invited to the [[2016 Liberty Bowl (December)|Liberty Bowl]] where they defeated [[2016 TCU Horned Frogs football team|TCU]].\n\n==Previous season==\nThe [[2015 Georgia Bulldogs football team]] was the favorite to win the Eastern Division. The Bulldogs started off the season 4\u20130 with SEC wins over [[2015 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]] 31\u201314 and [[2015 South Carolina Gamecocks football team|South Carolina]] 52\u201320, where quarterback [[Greyson Lambert]] set a NCAA record for completion percentage in a game with 96% (24/25). On October 3, the #13 [[2015 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]] came to Athens and defeated the Bulldogs 38\u201310. The next week the Dawgs traveled to [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]] to face the [[2015 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee Volunteers]]. On Georgia's first offensive play of the game, Bulldog's running back [[Nick Chubb]] was tackled on the sideline and suffered a season-ending knee injury as Georgia loss their second game of the season. Three weeks later, the Bulldogs suffered their third loss of the season during the [[World's Largest Outdoor Cocktail Party]] at [[EverBank Field]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida]] to the [[2015 Florida Gators football team|Florida Gators]] 27\u20133, where third-string quarterback Faton Bauta started. The Bulldogs finish the regular season on a four-game winning streak including road wins over the [[2015 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]] 20\u201313 and the [[2015 Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football team|Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets]] 13\u20137. The day after the Georgia Tech game, head coach [[Mark Richt]] was fired after 15 seasons of head coach. Richt had a record of 145\u201351 as head coach of the Bulldogs. Georgia finished the season with a win over the [[2015 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State Nittany Lions]] in the [[2016 TaxSlayer Bowl (January)|Taxslayer Bowl]] 24\u201317 under intermediate head coach [[Bryan McClendon]] in Jacksonville. The bowl win gave the Bulldogs a final 2015 season record of 10-3, which gave the senior class a total of 40 wins.\n\n==Coaching changes==\nAfter the 2015 regular season, Georgia's athletic director [[Greg McGarity]] fired head coach [[Mark Richt]] after 15 seasons with an overall 145\u201351 record. Richt was replaced with former Georgia football player [[Kirby Smart]], who, at the time, was [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]'s [[defensive coordinator]]. Smart played for the Bulldogs from 1995 to 1998 for coaches [[Ray Goff]] and [[Jim Donnan]] and was defensive coordinator at Alabama from 2008 to 2015 under head coach [[Nick Saban]]. [[Jeremy Pruitt]], who was defensive coordinator for Georgia from 2014 to 2015, accepted a position as the defensive coordinator for Alabama to replace Smart.\n\n==2016 recruiting class==\n{{College Athlete Recruit Start|collapse=yes|year=2016}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = [[Isaac Nauta]]\n| position   = #1 TE\n| hometown   = [[Bradenton, FL]]\n| highschool = [[IMG Academy]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 4\n| weight = 235\n| commitdate   = 1/9/16\n| scout stars  = 5\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 5\n| espn stars   = 5\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = [[Mecole Hardman]]\n| position   = #2 ATH\n| hometown   = [[Elberton, GA]]\n| highschool = [[Elbert County High School]]\n| feet   = 5\n| inches = 10\n| weight = 171\n| commitdate   = 2/3/16\n| scout stars  = 5\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 5\n| espn stars   = 4\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = [[Jacob Eason]]\n| position   = #1 QB\n| hometown   = [[Lake Stevens, WA]]\n| highschool = [[Lake Stevens High School]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 5\n| weight = 207\n| commitdate   = 7/9/14\n| scout stars  = 5\n| rivals stars = 5\n| 247 stars    = 5\n| espn stars   = 4\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = Charlie Woerner\n| position   = #4 ATH\n| hometown   = [[Tiger, GA]]\n| highschool = [[Rabun County High School]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 5\n| weight = 220\n| commitdate   = 7/23/15\n| scout stars  = 4\n| rivals stars = 4\n| 247 stars    = 4\n| espn stars   = 4\n}}\n{{College Athlete Recruit Entry\n| recruit    = [[Javon Wims]]\n| position   = #3 WR (JC)\n| hometown   = [[Miami, FL]]\n| highschool = [[Hinds Community College|Hinds C.C. (MS)]]\n| feet   = 6\n| inches = 4\n| weight = 20